<Document>
<name>Schwarzwaldhochstraße — Black Forest High Road</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Schwarzwaldhochstraße — Black Forest High Road</h2><p><i>Germany · B500 from Baden-Baden to Freudenstadt</i></p><p><b>Germany's first scenic mountain road built specifically for cars (1932). Spruce, fog, cuckoo clocks.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>44 km (27 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October; dramatic in fog and snow</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Fog (frequent), motorcyclists in formation, deer, ice in winter</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>70</td></tr></table><hr><p>Built 1932–33 as Germany's first scenic mountain road specifically for cars. The Black Forest is dark by design — the spruce forests are so dense that midday feels like dusk, hence Schwarzwald, 'Black Forest.' Cuckoo clocks were invented here in the 1730s, perfected at Triberg. The Mummelsee is a glacial tarn with a Grimm-Brothers folklore of water sprites; legend says anyone who throws in a coin will return one day. Drive on a misty autumn morning — the forest writes its own atmosphere. Pair with a drive south along the B500 through Triberg (highest waterfall in Germany) for a longer Black Forest day.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Baden-Baden</b> — Belle-Époque spa town. Roman thermal baths still operate (Friedrichsbad, 19th-century Roman-Irish bathing ritual). The Casino is older than Monte Carlo's.</li><li><b>Hornisgrinde</b> — Highest summit in the northern Black Forest (1,164 m). Boardwalk through bog moss and stunted pines; old observation tower.</li><li><b>Mummelsee</b> — Glacial tarn at 1,036 m, ringed by spruce. Folkloric water sprites supposedly inhabit it; rowboats for hire in summer.</li><li><b>Allerheiligen Waterfalls (spur)</b> — Seven cascades dropping 90 m through a slot ravine, with a ruined 1196 monastery at the top. 30 min walk down/up.</li><li><b>Freudenstadt market square</b> — Largest market square in Germany — 219 m × 216 m. Founded 1599 as a model planned town. Rebuilt after WWII destruction.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
